WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.010 --> 00:00:04.420
In this video we will look at 6 hard
surface techniques that changed how I worked.

00:00:04.930 --> 00:00:09.820
I have been creating 3D work
professionally for 20 years now, that is

00:00:09.830 --> 00:00:13.280
to say I have come across my fair share
of hard surface challenges.

00:00:13.610 --> 00:00:17.140
In this video I am going to share some of
my top techniques that I wish I had known

00:00:17.150 --> 00:00:21.820
years earlier and that have saved me
hours and hours of frustration.

00:00:23.390 --> 00:00:27.700
Hard surfaces usually feature a lot of
flat surfaces with right angles mainly

00:00:27.710 --> 00:00:31.200
due to the not overly malleable materials involved.

00:00:31.550 --> 00:00:34.360
I am thinking metal, wood and plastic.

00:00:34.570 --> 00:00:39.140
However, these things can still be bent,
cut and moulded into curved shapes.

00:00:39.490 --> 00:00:41.580
Lets take this design for example.

00:00:41.730 --> 00:00:43.540
We could start with a very high poly

00:00:43.550 --> 00:00:48.920
mesh, but what we gain in resolution we
lose in control, even with proportional editing.

00:00:49.290 --> 00:00:53.140
So lets look at keeping this mesh density
super low and controllable while having

00:00:53.150 --> 00:00:55.660
this high resolution smooth outcome.

00:00:56.670 --> 00:00:59.000
So lets move this aside and I am just

00:00:59.010 --> 00:01:04.840
going to shift and right click to drop
the cursor and shift a cylinder.

00:01:05.230 --> 00:01:07.500
We only need about 16 vertices here.

00:01:07.970 --> 00:01:10.460
Jumping into edit mode lets scale along

00:01:10.470 --> 00:01:13.220
the Y, something like that looks good.

00:01:13.870 --> 00:01:15.740
And in poly select lets do top and

00:01:15.750 --> 00:01:21.260
bottom, eye to inset and then right click
bridge faces.

00:01:21.270 --> 00:01:22.880
Lets just move it out the way a little bit.

00:01:23.010 --> 00:01:23.620
There we go.

00:01:23.850 --> 00:01:28.480
Now we have some larger bevels here, so
lets just go into edge mode, select

00:01:28.490 --> 00:01:31.000
these, bevel, that looks good.

00:01:31.110 --> 00:01:32.440
Maybe lets increase it a tad.

00:01:33.250 --> 00:01:35.740
And one on the inside here and bevel.

00:01:36.910 --> 00:01:37.760
Cool, that looks good.

00:01:37.890 --> 00:01:44.900
Now for the front section here we can
select these group of polygons, like so.

00:01:45.290 --> 00:01:50.440
Hit E to extrude out, scale down along
the Y, lets move it back a little bit.

00:01:50.930 --> 00:01:54.260
And then assuming you have loop tools
enabled, which you may need to do so from

00:01:54.270 --> 00:02:00.640
the addons menu in the preferences, we
can right click, loop tools, circle.

00:02:01.430 --> 00:02:06.760
I am just going to scale that down, hit
extrude, inset with I and then one more extrude

00:02:06.770 --> 00:02:07.940
to go in
.

00:02:07.970 --> 00:02:11.640
Ok, we have roughly the same shape but
with very low polys.

00:02:11.650 --> 00:02:16.180
Now lets look at how we can make it nice
and smooth, but with hard edges.

00:02:16.310 --> 00:02:20.420
Firstly, lets add a subd modifier with
CTRL and 3.

00:02:20.430 --> 00:02:25.880
We have the smooth down, but not the hard
edges, so lets go into edit mode and lets

00:02:25.890 --> 00:02:28.980
select one of the edges in edge mode.

00:02:28.990 --> 00:02:31.760
And we can use SHIFT G and then face

00:02:31.770 --> 00:02:37.380
angles to select edges with the adjacent
faces at a certain angle, which we can

00:02:37.390 --> 00:02:40.340
dial in here, but that looks good to me.

00:02:40.350 --> 00:02:43.460
So lets SHIFT E to create the crease,

00:02:43.470 --> 00:02:44.420
looks good.

00:02:44.430 --> 00:02:47.160
We need a few more creases here, so

00:02:47.370 --> 00:02:51.800
again, lets select that edge, face angle and
SHIFT E.

00:02:51.990 --> 00:02:52.700
Ok, cool.

00:02:52.710 --> 00:02:55.300
Now we also have a couple more edges here

00:02:55.310 --> 00:03:02.480
that we need to select to match this
style and underneath we don't have any

00:03:02.490 --> 00:03:06.760
sharpness at all, so lets just select
that edge loop with ALT, SHIFT E again

00:03:06.770 --> 00:03:10.140
and reduce to nothing, just make sure
that is minus 1.

00:03:10.150 --> 00:03:13.360
I'm just going to move this edge up a
little bit to match.

00:03:13.390 --> 00:03:18.940
Ok, cool, now we have the nice sharp
edges, so lets just shade smooth and see

00:03:18.950 --> 00:03:20.720
what we've got here.

00:03:20.730 --> 00:03:23.000
Just going to hide all of the wireframes

00:03:23.010 --> 00:03:26.400
with ALT SHIFT and Z to switch off the overlays.

00:03:26.410 --> 00:03:28.700
Its looking ok, but its not quite as nice

00:03:28.710 --> 00:03:32.820
and creased as this one, so lets add a
bevel as well.

00:03:32.830 --> 00:03:36.700
Go into edit mode, select one of the
edges with a crease on, and if we SHIFT

00:03:36.710 --> 00:03:41.420
and G, we can select all of the creases
and then CTRL and E, edge bevel, and

00:03:41.430 --> 00:03:43.660
we'll just add an edge bevel weight of 1.

00:03:43.670 --> 00:03:45.720
Now we can add a modifier, search for

00:03:46.530 --> 00:03:53.660
bevel, limit method to weight, that
weight we just created, shading, harden normals.

00:03:53.670 --> 00:03:59.320
Now if we switch off our overlays, we
have a really nice look with nice sharp edges.

00:03:59.330 --> 00:04:03.020
Lets say you're being a productivity
wizard and you're only working on half of

00:04:03.030 --> 00:04:05.940
your model, knowing you can add a mirror modifier.

00:04:05.950 --> 00:04:09.240
If we were to do so now, you can see that

00:04:09.250 --> 00:04:13.060
we have odd pinching here and its not
looking particularly nice, and this is

00:04:13.070 --> 00:04:17.040
because our mirror modifier is happening
after the fact.

00:04:17.050 --> 00:04:20.120
Thankfully there is quite a cool way you
can remedy this, and that is because as

00:04:20.130 --> 00:04:23.020
of 4 .2 you can pin modifiers.

00:04:23.030 --> 00:04:25.100
So if we select bevel for example, we can

00:04:25.110 --> 00:04:29.020
pin to last, and likewise on our subdivision.

00:04:29.030 --> 00:04:31.220
Now if we add our mirror modifier, it

00:04:31.230 --> 00:04:34.100
happens before our pinned items in the stack.

00:04:34.110 --> 00:04:35.820
Really handy.

00:04:35.830 --> 00:04:39.380
Now this one took me far too long to
realise, I'm sure a lot of you know you

00:04:39.390 --> 00:04:45.280
can add cables by going into a curve,
adding say a bezier curve, going into the

00:04:45.290 --> 00:04:51.340
curve options and geometry under depth,
just cranking things up a little bit like so.

00:04:51.490 --> 00:04:56.380
However, I used to then go in and start
manipulating these points and try and

00:04:56.390 --> 00:05:00.580
snap and rotate and arrange things, and
it just took a little too long.

00:05:00.590 --> 00:05:06.280
And I find it considerably easier to just
select all and delete all vertices, jump

00:05:06.290 --> 00:05:11.220
in to the draw mode and draw from the cursor.

00:05:11.230 --> 00:05:12.960
Now if we go into orthographic here, I'm

00:05:12.970 --> 00:05:17.700
just going to snap the side, lets go to
wireframe, we can draw the curve that we

00:05:18.190 --> 00:05:19.960
want, something like that looks good.

00:05:19.970 --> 00:05:21.480
And you can see that the calculation of

00:05:21.490 --> 00:05:25.900
the bezier handles is already pretty good
and only needs a little bit of clean up

00:05:25.910 --> 00:05:27.660
to finish.

00:05:27.670 --> 00:05:30.120
On a side note, you can also go into edit

00:05:30.130 --> 00:05:35.100
mode and just check surface and now you
can draw your cables all over your

00:05:35.110 --> 00:05:39.560
geometry and it sticks nicely to it like so.

00:05:39.570 --> 00:05:41.740
Right angle joins like this appear quite

00:05:41.750 --> 00:05:45.700
a lot for me, particularly in hard
surface modelling for handles and the like.

00:05:45.710 --> 00:05:50.120
Thankfully its quite easy to put together
if you have your two cylinders here in

00:05:50.130 --> 00:05:54.440
place and they are joined into one
object, we can select the edges here,

00:05:54.450 --> 00:05:58.400
right click and then go to bridge edge loops.

00:05:58.410 --> 00:06:01.100
And then under number of cuts, you can

00:06:01.110 --> 00:06:07.340
add say 5 and adjust the smoothness
factor to your liking.

00:06:07.350 --> 00:06:08.980
And done.

00:06:08.990 --> 00:06:10.820
Some things are just painful to add to

00:06:10.830 --> 00:06:15.100
existing geometry without having to
seriously mess up your beautiful

00:06:15.110 --> 00:06:17.900
underlying base mesh, so why not just
stick it on top.

00:06:17.930 --> 00:06:20.420
Well, lets look at how to set that up.

00:06:20.570 --> 00:06:22.320
Firstly, this is the item we want to

00:06:22.330 --> 00:06:27.500
stick on the underside of our craft here,
just like a pulse engine of sorts.

00:06:27.610 --> 00:06:32.780
Firstly, we need to make sure our origin
point is snapped to the bottom, so I'm

00:06:32.790 --> 00:06:38.540
just going to go into edit mode, edge,
select the loop with ALT and left click,

00:06:38.550 --> 00:06:41.760
and then snap our cursor to it with SHIFT
and S.

00:06:41.770 --> 00:06:45.840
Hitting tab to go back out into object
mode, we can go to object, set origin,

00:06:45.850 --> 00:06:47.380
origin to 3D cursor.

00:06:47.390 --> 00:06:49.700
Now under our snap options here, we can

00:06:49.710 --> 00:06:53.740
make sure we are on face and align
rotation to target.

00:06:53.750 --> 00:06:58.640
And that affords us the ability to just
hit G, hold down control and snap our

00:06:58.650 --> 00:07:01.000
item on the underside like so.

00:07:01.010 --> 00:07:03.200
Now this isn't hugely convincing as a

00:07:03.210 --> 00:07:07.800
join here, but we're only just getting
started, so to make it a little bit more

00:07:08.010 --> 00:07:13.320
convincing, we can go into edit mode and
select these outer polys, go over to our

00:07:13.330 --> 00:07:18.420
vertex options, create a new vertex
group, let's just leave it called group,

00:07:18.430 --> 00:07:19.880
and click assign.

00:07:19.890 --> 00:07:21.680
Now if we jump out into object mode and

00:07:21.690 --> 00:07:28.800
move over to our modifiers, we can add a
new modifier, and search for shrink wrap.

00:07:28.810 --> 00:07:30.980
Let's move it to the top of the stack.

00:07:30.990 --> 00:07:33.260
Now we can select our target, the main

00:07:33.270 --> 00:07:38.800
base of the ship here, and restrict this
effect by that vertex group we just created.

00:07:38.810 --> 00:07:44.320
Now we can duplicate this over the bottom
to our hearts content.

00:07:44.330 --> 00:07:48.540
Now I'm sure some of you can see that the
join here is still quite abrupt,

00:07:48.550 --> 00:07:52.620
particularly in rendered mode, and it's
not really fooling anyone.

00:07:52.630 --> 00:07:59.300
Thankfully we can use the normal data
from the object which we are stuck to and

00:07:59.310 --> 00:08:01.400
apply it to this object.

00:08:01.410 --> 00:08:03.380
And to do so, with the object selected,

00:08:03.390 --> 00:08:10.620
we can go add modifier, search for data
transfer, select our source object, and

00:08:10.630 --> 00:08:17.360
go down to face corner data, let's just
expand that, and we want the custom

00:08:17.630 --> 00:08:23.100
normals, and the option we want is
nearest face interpolated, and I find

00:08:23.110 --> 00:08:25.400
this to be the smoothest result.

00:08:25.410 --> 00:08:27.420
And as you can see, it looks like it

00:08:27.430 --> 00:08:30.280
almost doesn't exist at all with some
very light shading.

00:08:30.290 --> 00:08:34.780
Thankfully we can once again take
advantage of our vertex group to isolate

00:08:34.790 --> 00:08:39.020
the effect, and now you can see,
particularly compared to the old method,

00:08:39.030 --> 00:08:41.500
it looks considerably better.

00:08:41.510 --> 00:08:44.280
So let's just shift select all the

00:08:44.290 --> 00:08:49.640
remaining items, and then the item with
the data transfer, and then go to this

00:08:49.650 --> 00:08:52.900
little dropdown here, and copy to selected.

00:08:52.910 --> 00:08:53.800
Excellent.

00:08:53.810 --> 00:08:58.700
I hope some of these techniques have
helped, now this model was built

00:08:58.710 --> 00:09:03.260
exclusively to demo most of these
techniques, but if you had fun and you'd

00:09:03.270 --> 00:09:07.380
be interested in learning something a
little bit more, then you might like

00:09:07.390 --> 00:09:13.040
Robotic Planet, a full robot creation
course over at CG Boost Academy.

00:09:13.050 --> 00:09:17.960
We walk through entire robot creations as
well as tackling even more tips and tricks.

00:09:17.970 --> 00:09:21.540
Enrolling in the course also gives you
access to the CG Boost community where

00:09:21.550 --> 00:09:25.380
you can comment, share ideas, or get help
on particular parts of the course.

